<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1941,2038]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
The two species of this group are characterized by the last segment of the male antenna, which is apically curved downwards (
<figureCitation box="[296,380,1977,2002]" captionStart="FIGURE 10 – 15. 10" captionStartId="8.[151,249,1926,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,769,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,769,1904]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 10 – 15. 10: Hoplitis allii, clypeus of female. 11: Hoplitis allii, terga 4 – 7 of male. 12: Hoplitis onychophora, terga 4 – 7 of male. 13: Hoplitis allii, antenna of male. 14: Hoplitis allii, sterna 1 – 2 of male. 15: Hoplitis onychophora, sterna 1 – 2 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230855/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">
Fig. 
<number box="[350,380,1978,2002]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), the presence of two teeth at the base of the male hind coxa and the form of male tergum 
<number box="[1415,1431,1978,2001]" pageId="6" pageNumber="167" value="7.0">7</number>
, which laterally possesses two slender processes (
<figureCitation box="[699,834,2013,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 10 – 15. 10" captionStartId="8.[151,249,1926,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,769,1903]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,769,1904]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 10 – 15. 10: Hoplitis allii, clypeus of female. 11: Hoplitis allii, terga 4 – 7 of male. 12: Hoplitis onychophora, terga 4 – 7 of male. 13: Hoplitis allii, antenna of male. 14: Hoplitis allii, sterna 1 – 2 of male. 15: Hoplitis onychophora, sterna 1 – 2 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230855/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="167">Figs. 11, 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
